dya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Campania","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Mario, Angelo, Gino, Alfonso, Antonio, Biagio, Caesar, Dino, Falco, Sisto, Alessandra, Amerigo, Carlo, Cosmo.  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Jorge, Luis, Roberto, Agustin, Amado.","Italian and Spanish: metonymic occupational name for a bell-ringer or bell-maker, from <i>campana</i> ‘bell’ (abbreviated from the Latin phrase <i>vasa campana</i> ‘Campanian vessels’, since bells were first produced in Campania)."],"variants":[{"name":"Campanella","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Salvatore, Santo, Sal, Rocco, Calogero, Cosmo, Domenic, Vito, Aldo, Annamarie, Antonio.","Italian: from a diminutive of <i>campana</i> ‘bell’, applied as a metonymic occupational name for a maker of small bells or handbells, or as a means of distinguishing one branch or member of a family called   Campana   from another."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud de Campania was born on 8 January 1349, in Norwich, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. She married John Fitz Ranulf on 20 May 1371, in Norwich, Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 2 daughters."},"et":{"8 January 1349–":"8. jaanuar 1349–Surnud","1344–1385":"1344–1385","1372–Female":"1372–Surnud","1374–1405":"1374–1405","1376–Female":"1376–Surnud","1378–1454":"1378–1454","1349–Female":"1349–Surnud","22 March 1378":"22. märts 1378","4 February 1372":"4. veebruar 1372","4 June 1376":"4. juuni 1376","1374":"1374","1385":"1385","1372":"1372","8 January 1349":"8. jaanuar 1349","20 May 1371":"20. mai 1371","1349":"1349","1378":"1378","1454":"1454","1344":"1344","1376":"1376","1405":"1405","Norwich, Norfolk, England":"Norwich, Norfolk, England","York, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"York, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Norwich, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Norwich, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Spennithorne, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Spennithorne, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"8 January 1349–":"8. tammikuuta 1349–Kuollut","1344–1385":"1344–1385","1372–Female":"1372–Kuollut","1374–1405":"1374–1405","1376–Female":"1376–Kuollut","1378–1454":"1378–1454","1349–Female":"1349–Kuollut","22 March 1378":"22. maaliskuuta 1378","4 February 1372":"4. helmikuuta 1372"